 or timid person, from Old French <i>levre</i> ‘hare’ (from Latin <i>lepus</i>, genitive <i>leporis</i>). It may also have been a metonymic occupational name for a hunter of hares.","English: topographic name for someone who lived in a place thickly grown with rushes, from Old English <i>lǣfer</i> ‘rush, reed, iris’. Compare   Laver  . Great and Little Lever in Greater Manchester are named with this word (in a collective sense), so the surname may also be a habitational name from these places.","Dutch and North German: from the medieval personal names <i>Lever</i>, a variant of <i>Liever</i> (see   Lieber  ), and <i>Levert</i>, a variant of <i>Lievert</i> (see   Liebhart  ). This surname is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Levis","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Levis</i> (Old English <i>Lēofhyse</i>, from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>hyse</i> ‘youth, warrior’).","English: occasionally perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Leve</i>, Old English <i>Lēofa</i> (male) or <i>Lēofe</i> (female), which derive from <i>lēof</i> ‘dear, beloved’, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, since <i>Leve</i> is attested as a medieval surname.","English: perhaps also from Middle English <i>lef</i>, <i>leve</i>, plural <i>leves</i>, possibly representing Old English <i>lēaf</i> ‘leaf, foliage’ in some topographic sense, or Old English <i>hlīf</i> ‘shelter’."]}]},{"name":"Geoffroi","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Geoffrey</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffroi II de Lèves was born in 1155, in Lèves, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France, his father, Milon de Lèves de Totes, was 30 and his mother, Mabile de Tre